APPENDIX C: GOVERNANCE & LEGAL FRAMEWORKS

C1: Draft Charter for the International Space Resource Authority (ISRA)

Article I: Establishment and Principles

1.1 Establishment
The International Space Resource Authority (ISRA) is established as a specialized agency under the auspices of the United Nations Committee on the Peaceful Uses of Outer Space (UNCOPUOS).

1.2 Core Principles

· Common Heritage Principle: Space resources are the common heritage of humanity
· Equitable Access: All nations shall benefit from resource utilization
· Peaceful Purposes: Resources shall be used exclusively for peaceful purposes
· Sustainability: Utilization shall avoid harmful contamination and preserve scientific value
· Transparency: All activities shall be registered and monitored

Article II: Functions and Powers

2.1 Licensing Authority
ISRA shall issue licenses for:

· Prospecting (5-year term, non-exclusive)
· Exploration (10-year term, exclusive to area)
· Extraction (20-year term, renewable)

2.2 Area Management

· Designation of "scientific preserves" (no extraction)
· Zoning for different activities (mining, habitation, conservation)
· Conflict resolution between operators

2.3 Royalty Collection

· Ad valorem royalty: 3% of gross value of extracted resources
· Fixed fee: $10,000/km²/year for exclusive areas
· Revenue distribution: 50% to operations, 30% to developing nations' space programs, 20% to environmental restoration fund

Article III: Licensing Process

3.1 Application Requirements

· Technical and financial capability demonstration
· Environmental impact assessment
· Reclamation and decommissioning plan
· Safety and emergency response protocols
· Benefit-sharing plan for humanity

3.2 Evaluation Criteria

· Technical feasibility (30% weight)
· Environmental protection (25% weight)
· Benefit to humanity (20% weight)
· Financial viability (15% weight)
· Safety record (10% weight)

3.3 Due Diligence

· Background checks on corporate structure
· Verification of funding sources
· Assessment of past compliance with space law

Article IV: Monitoring and Enforcement

4.1 Reporting Requirements

· Monthly production reports
· Quarterly environmental monitoring
· Annual financial audits
· Incident reporting within 24 hours

4.2 Inspection Rights

· ISRA inspectors have right of access to all facilities
· Remote monitoring via telemetry
· Random on-site inspections with 48-hour notice

4.3 Enforcement Mechanisms

· Level 1: Warning and corrective action plan
· Level 2: Fines up to 10% of annual revenue
· Level 3: Suspension of operations for up to 1 year
· Level 4: Revocation of license and blacklisting

4.4 Dispute Resolution

· Mandatory mediation for all disputes
· Binding arbitration for technical matters
· Appeals panel of 5 independent experts
· Final appeal to International Court of Justice

Article V: Benefit-Sharing Mechanism

5.1 Technology Transfer Pool

· Licensees contribute 1% of revenue to technology pool
· Developing nations can access pool for space technology
· Mandatory licensing of non-critical patents at fair rates

5.2 Capacity Building

· Training programs for developing nations' space agencies
· Scholarship programs in relevant fields
· Joint mission opportunities

5.3 Economic Development Fund

· Grants for terrestrial sustainable development projects
· Priority for climate change adaptation
· Focus on space-related education and infrastructure

Article VI: Organizational Structure

6.1 Governing Council

· 25 member states (rotating)
· 5 permanent seats for major spacefaring nations
· Decisions by 2/3 majority
· Meets biannually

6.2 Technical Committee

· 15 independent experts
· 5-year terms, renewable once
· Advises on licensing and standards

6.3 Secretariat

· Executive Director appointed by Governing Council
· 200 professional staff maximum
· Headquarters in Vienna, with regional offices

6.4 Budget

· Initial capitalization: $500M from founding members
· Annual operating budget: $100M
· Funded by licensing fees and royalties

Article VII: Amendment and Review

7.1 Amendment Process

· Proposed by 1/3 of Governing Council members
· Ratified by 3/4 of member states
· Enters force 1 year after ratification

7.2 Review Clause

· Comprehensive review every 10 years
· Special review if >10% of members request
· Sunset provisions for temporary measures

---

C2: Template for Multiplanetary Alliance Treaty

Preamble

The States Parties to this Treaty,

Inspired by the great prospects opening up before humanity as a result of entering outer space,

Recognizing the common interest of all humanity in the exploration and use of outer space for peaceful purposes,

Believing that the exploration and use of outer space should be carried on for the benefit of all peoples,

Desiring to contribute to broad international cooperation in the scientific, legal, and commercial aspects of the exploration and use of outer space,

Have agreed as follows:

Article 1: Definitions

For the purposes of this Treaty:

(a) "Celestial body" includes the Moon, planets, asteroids, comets, and other natural objects in outer space;

(b) "Space resource" means any naturally occurring abiotic resource in situ in outer space;

(c) "Heritage site" means an area of outstanding scientific or cultural value requiring special protection;

(d) "Operator" means any entity conducting activities under this Treaty.

Article 2: Principles of Cooperation

2.1 Mutual Assistance
States Parties shall render all possible assistance to operators of other States Parties in the event of accident, distress, or emergency.

2.2 Information Sharing
States Parties shall share scientific and technical information resulting from activities under this Treaty.

2.3 Non-Interference
States Parties shall not interfere with the activities of other States Parties conducted in accordance with this Treaty.

Article 3: Resource Rights and Responsibilities

3.1 Right of Use
States Parties recognize the right to extract and utilize space resources, provided such activities are conducted in accordance with this Treaty.

3.2 Non-Appropriation
No State Party may claim sovereignty over any celestial body or portion thereof.

3.3 Due Regard
Activities shall be conducted with due regard to the corresponding interests of all other States Parties.

Article 4: Environmental Protection

4.1 Planetary Protection
States Parties shall implement measures to prevent forward and backward biological contamination.

4.2 Preservation of Heritage
States Parties shall preserve areas of special scientific interest, including historic landing sites.

4.3 Waste Management
States Parties shall minimize space debris and ensure safe disposal of waste.

Article 5: Safety Standards

5.1 Technical Standards
States Parties shall adopt common technical standards for:

· Life support systems
· Radiation protection
· Space traffic management
· Emergency response

5.2 Certification
Operators must obtain certification for all critical systems from an approved certification body.

5.3 Incident Investigation
Joint investigation teams shall be formed for serious incidents involving multiple States Parties.

Article 6: Dispute Settlement

6.1 Consultation
States Parties shall seek to resolve disputes through consultation and negotiation.

6.2 Mediation
If not resolved within 6 months, disputes shall be referred to mediation.

6.3 Arbitration
If mediation fails, disputes shall be settled by binding arbitration under the Permanent Court of Arbitration Optional Rules for Arbitration of Disputes Relating to Outer Space Activities.

Article 7: Implementation and Monitoring

7.1 National Implementation
Each State Party shall adopt laws and regulations to implement this Treaty.

7.2 Reporting
States Parties shall submit annual reports on activities under this Treaty.

7.3 Review Conference
A review conference shall be held every 5 years to assess implementation.

Article 8: Final Clauses

8.1 Signature and Ratification
This Treaty shall be open for signature by all States and shall be subject to ratification.

8.2 Entry into Force
This Treaty shall enter into force 30 days after the deposit of the twentieth instrument of ratification.

8.3 Amendments
Amendments shall be adopted by a two-thirds majority of States Parties and enter into force for accepting States Parties.

8.4 Withdrawal
A State Party may withdraw by written notification, effective one year after receipt.

IN WITNESS WHEREOF the undersigned, being duly authorized thereto by their respective Governments, have signed this Treaty.

DONE at [Location] on [Date] in the Arabic, Chinese, English, French, Russian and Spanish languages, all texts being equally authentic.

